[30;1m523 | [0m[35mwith unicode text without raising a :exc:`UnicodeError`.  What seems to occur[0m
[30;1m524 | [0m[35min these libraries is that the library has functions that expect to receive[0m
[30;1m525 | [0m[35ma :class:`unicode` string.  However, internally, those functions call other[0m
[30;1m526 | [0m[35mfunctions that expect to receive a byte :class:`str`.  The programmer of the[0m
[30;1m527 | [0m[35mAPI was smart enough to convert from a :class:`unicode` string to a byte[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m340[0m[34m of [0m[33m735[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m422 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m423 | [0m[35mNext you need to think about the type of data that you're receiving.  If it's[0m
[30;1m424 | [0m[35mtextual data, (for instance, this is a chat client and the user is typing[0m
[30;1m425 | [0m[35mmessages that they expect to be read by another person) it probably makes sense to[0m
[30;1m426 | [0m[35mtake in :class:`unicode` strings and do the conversion inside your function.[0m
[30;1m427 | [0m[35mOn the other hand, if this is a lower level function that's passing data into[0m
[30;1m428 | [0m[35ma network socket, it probably should be taking byte :class:`str` instead.[0m

[30;1m456 | [0m[35m===========================================[0m
[30;1m457 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m461 | [0m[35mstring.  When that happens, this API returns the raw byte :class:`str` instead[0m

[30;1m436 | [0m[35m========================[0m
[30;1m437 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m439 | [0m[35mimmediately output that data anywhere.  Just as when writing external data,[0m
[30;1m440 | [0m[35myou should think about both what your function is going to do with the data[0m
[30;1m441 | [0m[35meventually and what the caller of your function is thinking that they're[0m

[30;1m404 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m405 | [0m[35mNot all functions have a return value.  Sometimes a function is there to[0m
[30;1m406 | [0m[35minteract with something external to python, for instance, writing a file out[0m
[30;1m407 | [0m[35mto disk or a method exists to update the internal state of a data structure.[0m
[30;1m408 | [0m[35mOne of the main questions with these APIs is whether to take byte[0m
[30;1m409 | [0m[35m:class:`str`, :class:`unicode` string, or both.  The answer depends on your[0m
[30;1m410 | [0m[35muse case but I'll give some examples here.[0m

[30;1m106 | [0m[35m* The Minor version increments for any backwards incompatible API changes.[0m
[30;1m107 | [0m[35m  When this is updated, we reset micro to zero.[0m

[30;1m490 | [0m[35mSo the code raises an exception where it's not immediately obvious that[0m
[30;1m491 | [0m[35m:func:`os.listdir` is at fault.[0m

[30;1m455 | [0m[35mReturning unicode unless a conversion fails[0m
[30;1m456 | [0m[35m===========================================[0m
[30;1m457 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m458 | [0m[35mThis type of API usually deals with byte :class:`str` at some point and[0m
[30;1m459 | [0m[35mconverts it to :class:`unicode` because it's usually thought to be text.[0m

[30;1m461 | [0m[35mstring.  When that happens, this API returns the raw byte :class:`str` instead[0m

[30;1m425 | [0m[35mmessages that they expect to be read by another person) it probably makes sense to[0m

[30;1m427 | [0m[35mOn the other hand, if this is a lower level function that's passing data into[0m
[30;1m428 | [0m[35ma network socket, it probably should be taking byte :class:`str` instead.[0m

[30;1m191 | [0m[35mencoded with one of UTF32be, UTF32le, UTF16be, UTF16le, or :term:`UTF-8`.  It further[0m

[30;1m207 | [0m[35m-----------------------------------------[0m

[30;1m209 | [0m[35mIn English, there's a saying "waiting for the other shoe to drop".  It means[0m
[30;1m210 | [0m[35mthat when one event (usually bad) happens, you come to expect another event[0m
[30;1m211 | [0m[35m(usually worse) to come after.  In this case we have two other shoes.[0m
[30;1m212 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m213 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m38 | [0m[35m    In many cases, it is better to convert to :class:`unicode`, operate on the[0m
[30;1m39 | [0m[35m    strings, then convert back to :term:`UTF-8`.  :class:`unicode` type can[0m
[30;1m40 | [0m[35m    handle many of these functions itself.  For those that it doesn't[0m
[30;1m41 | [0m[35m    (removing control characters from length calculations, for instance) the[0m
[30;1m42 | [0m[35m    code to do so with a :class:`unicode` type is often simpler.[0m
[30;1m43 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m44 | [0m[35m.. warning::[0m
